english:
  title: Inscriptional Eulogy for National Teacher Chinmyung at Jayun Temple on Waryong Mountain
  author: Kim Ku
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The National Teacher bore the dharma name Hunwon, with secular surname Lee, native of Suan County. His father, Teacher Deok, rose to the position of Director of the Capital Market Bureau. His mother, Lady Kim, was the daughter of Court Usher Yeolbo. She dreamed of drinking ambrosia and became pregnant. Born with luminous wisdom, he reverence for the Buddha's teaching from childhood. At thirteen, he entered the priesthood under his uncle, Master Poomil Yunson, receiving the complete precepts. Surpassing all in brilliance and learning, he mastered both inner and outer teachings, becoming foremost among the monks of Gul Mountain. He passed the highest examination in the Chan selection. With aspirations toward mountain wilderness, he vowed never to tread the path of secular fame. Staff in hand, he traveled widely, first visiting the sage Byeon at Double Peak, serving several years and penetrating his profound teachings. Then he approached the Caoxiside under Master Muui, receiving great praise. He also studied under National Teacher Cheongmin, and wherever he went, he pursued the subtle meanings, mastering the cases of the ancients, freely crossing the mysterious gateway and obtaining the eloquence of joyful speech.

    The Grand Commander, the Duke of Jinyang, admired his cultivation and memorialized the throne, securing his elevation to Triple Grand Master. He was appointed to lead the Jeong-hye Assembly. Soon finding the burdens of leadership wearisome, he repeatedly petitioned the Duke of Jinyang to decline, eventually gaining the title of Chan Master. Wishing not to be a temple abbot, he simply taught wherever he went, so the world called him Dharma Master though none spoke his name.

    In the year Eulsa, the Duke of Jinyang established the Chan Source Assembly with grand celebration, requesting the Master to preside. The following year, Byeong-o, the Master led two hundred refined monks to the capital, entering Chan Source. The High King specially appointed him Great Chan Master. The Duke composed a petition, sending envoys to request he ascend the teaching seat, becoming the successor to Cheongmin. Days later, the King himself visited, first presenting a golden brocade robe, then kneeling to submit his petition. The Master's dharma teaching greatly pleased the King. Though dwelling in the capital, the Master's heart remained in mountains and valleys. He repeatedly requested to return to the mountains, but the King would not permit it.

    In the year Imja, when Cheongmin approached his final nirvana, he entrusted the temple matters to the Master. The King then commanded him to reside at Caoxiside as the Fourth Patriarch, appointing palace attendants to accompany him. He entered in the twelfth month and again raised the wind of herding oxen. In autumn of Byeong-jin, seeking to serve as Dharma Master of Chan Source and appoint another in his place, he requested freedom to wander. Yet the court, regarding him as a field of blessing, continued unceasing veneration.

    In the year Muo, the King, deeply moved by the Master's virtue, wished to serve him with unparalleled reverence. He established the Office of Enshrinement and commanded Dansung Temple to send palace attendant Minister Choi Taek to receive him. The Master declined to accept the mandate. The attendant conveyed the King's earnest longing, and the Master reluctantly arose and traveled west. The King sent an escort and welcomed him to Jayun Temple. At that time there had been long drought, but that very evening sudden rain fell abundantly—all rejoiced and marveled. The King requested to receive him as one's teacher; on the eleventh day of the fifth month of Kimi year, he was invested as National Teacher. The King wished to perform the teacher's rituals personally but fell ill and could not. Soon after, the King ascended to heaven.

    Won-jong took the throne and, following his father's wishes, increased the honors of respect. Waryong Temple was designated as his teaching place. When the Master earnestly requested to retire, making this plea repeatedly, the King said: "I wish to keep the Master near to receive the shelter of dharma protection. Your intention is firm and immovable; yet I pray that whether near or far, your resolve remains unchanged, and forever may you bring blessings to the three realms of Korea." The King received him at the inner palace, performed the teacher's ritual with his own hands, personally presented meals, conversed gently, and at evening took leave, commanding palace attendants to escort him.

    In the tenth month of Gyeongsin year, he descended the mountain and entered the temple, ascending the teaching seat. When the Master entered the gate, the halls soared into space; gazing upon the streams and mountains, they seemed like a painting. The Master proclaimed: "The weary bird knows to return; heaven sent the old dragon to rest peacefully. You gathered ones—now the dragon sleeps. Where then is Compassionate Cloud?" After a long pause, he continued: "Traveling until reaching where waters have their source, sitting to watch clouds arise in time."

    From four directions students gathered like clouds. For twelve years he taught the dharma for the benefit of all beings. The crumbling halls he renewed and restored, and people said: "The opening patriarch Great Master Gyeong-kong has returned."

    The King's uncle, Great Master Gyeongji, in his youth received the tonsure from National Teacher Yuanjin of Yangsan and held the Master in deep reverence, serving with disciple's etiquette. After receiving imperial decree to transfer his registry to Gul Mountain as dharma heir of Poomil, he became abbot of Dansung Temple, frequently coming to pay respects. Thus was the Master honored by the great ones.

    In the eighth year of Zhiyuan, twelfth month, first day—the year Sinmi—in his chamber, he recited a verse:
    "Today the first of the twelfth month;
    Watching, the thirtieth approaches.
    When the thirtieth arrives,
    Let not right mindfulness be forgotten."

    On the seventh day he showed slight suffering. On the morning of the tenth, attending monks inquired. The Master raised eyes like Buddha's: "A bird flies through empty space, enters and dwells within the heart." His verse reply proceeded as always. He wrote a letter for the King, sealed his seal and sigil, entrusting them to his attendant. At the hour of application, he changed into his robe, sat upon the meditation bench, folded his hands upon his chest, and peacefully manifested nirvana. His face shone like powdered jade; his limbs remained flexible as if alive.

    On the sixteenth day, his body was cremated at the rear of the temple. His disciples, carrying his testament and seal, hastened to report to the King, who grieved deeply. He was elevated to National Teacher, granted the posthumous name Chinmyung, and his stupa named Puguang. The King commanded the Deputy Governor of Jinju and Minister of Revenue Seol Ang to complete the rites.

    On the seventeenth day of the second month of Imsin year, the stupa was erected on the western slope of the temple. He lived eighty-one years and had followed the monastic life for sixty-eight.

    The Master possessed compassionate heart to save all beings, meeting others with humility and modesty. His conduct bore no artifice; his words concealed nothing. His discourse held savor that made people delighted and tireless, beloved and reverenced. Throughout his life, his sitting place never knew warmth. Wherever he went, he took as his duty only the propagation of the dharma. In composing verses, he achieved perfect refinement with sharp novelty, all bearing the mark of his insight, awakening later students.

    Such was the outline of the Master's lifelong practice. I, having once received the grace of the dharma-milk given by the Buddha, found no way to repay. Moreover, the royal command came to compose words for stone. How could I presume to decline, claiming my language is rough? Thus I wet my brush and inscribed this inscription:

    *Beyond the hundred billion worlds,
    One Buddha hall exists—
    Without adornment of color,
    Eight faces gleam translucent.

    Each patriarch dwelling eternally,
    Clear wind sweeping the earth,
    From the Western Land through Central Land
    Reaching to the Eastern Sea—

    Poomil first proclaimed the dharma,
    Gaebop held the key of treasure.
    Bojo, Wongam, and Seongak—
    Successive patriarchs blazed forth.

    Crimson from heaven, indigo from earth,
    Our Master shone supreme.
    Ambrosia's auspicious sign
    Born through his mother's womb—

    The dharma vessel appearing,
    Compassion and wisdom always full.
    A thousand sages bowed as disciples,
    All turning their right shoulders as one.

    Humbly meeting all beings,
    His seat grew never warm.
    Though his trace receded,
    His name advanced first.

    Both court and common folk acclaimed—
    Become the King's own teacher.
    Ten thousand chariots bent their dignity,
    Grasping his robes and begging grace.

    When the former sovereign passed,
    The new king took the throne,
    Becoming model for two reigns,
    Fortune and merit spread wide.

    Wonderful function stretched in all directions—
    Human and heavenly realms revered him.
    The dharma rain sufficed;
    The dragon rested at Waryong.

    Clinging to scales to gain its moisture,
    Students gathered like clouds.
    Reaching eighty and one year,
    He hid his shadow in darkness.

    Singing as he departed,
    What was the melody's strain?
    White clouds vast and distant—
    One bird flying past.

    Within the fire, worldliness dissolved;
    The tower of pearls rises high.
    Spiritual light gleams ten thousand ages,
    Illuminating mountains and rivers.*
